w.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon bombing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Tamerlan Tsarnaev") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "FBI") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Chechnya") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Russia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Kyrgyzstan") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Massachusetts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US crime") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 15:41:38 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/boston-bombing-suspects-dzhokhar-tamerlan-tsarnaev") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T15:41:38Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407597205") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon bombing, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, Tamerlan Tsarnaev, FBI, Chechnya, Russia, Kyrgyzstan, United States, Massachusetts, US crime, Boston, World news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366558138370/Boston-bombing-suspects-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Uncredited/AP") (media:description nil "Boston bombing suspects Tamerlan Tsarnaev, left, and Dzhokhar Tsarnaev. Photograph: Uncredited/AP")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366558144330/Boston-bombing-suspects-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Uncredited/AP") (media:description nil "Boston bombing suspects Tamerlan Tsarnaev, left, and Dzhokhar Tsarnaev. Photograph: Uncredited/AP")))) ("Tim Coone obituary" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/11220?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Atim-coone%3A1897048&ch=From+the+Guardian&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Nicaragua+%28News%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful&c6=Chris+Taylor&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A41&c8=1897048&c9=Article&c10=Obituary&c13=Other+lives+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Tim+Coone+obituary&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FFrom+the+Guardian%2FNicaragua\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>Tim Coone, who has died of cancer aged 60, was a respected foreign correspondent whose life was changed by Nicaragua. He first headed there in 1981 in the optimistic early days of the Sandinista revolution, as a stringer for several media outlets including the BBC World Service, and from his base in the Nicaraguan capital, Managua, covered Central America for most of a turbulent decade, becoming the Financial Times's correspondent.</p><p>Ever resourceful, during the invasion of Panama in 1989, when the US military were preventing the Managua press corps from entering the country, Tim managed to charter a plane, inviting along fellow journalists. As the reporter Joe Gannon remembers: \"Tim being Tim it never occurred to him to take off on his own, get the scoop.\" His peers elected him president of the Managua Foreign Press Club.</p><p>He had brief spells in Argentina in the mid-80s and in Dublin in the 90s, where he clashed with his FT superiors over his take on the Northern Ireland story. In 1994 Tim moved to Mexico as a freelance, later working for the Economist Intelligence Unit.</p><p>He returned to Nicaragua in 1997 and devoted his energies to a project that had long fascinated him: to build a waterway connecting Nicaragua's Pacific coast with the Caribbean Sea. His cost-effective and environmentally sensitive Ecocanal plan attracted influential partners and official approval but to his disappointment the dream remained unfulfilled. Latterly Tim worked to promote renewable energy in Nicaragua.</p><p>He was born in Aberdeen, Maryland, the second son of Kenneth, a US serviceman, and Muriel, a British nurse. The family moved to the UK when Tim was a year old, and his parents subsequently divorced. After King Edward's school, Bath, and Teignmouth grammar school, Devon, he went to Imperial College London, but transferred to Newcastle University, where he completed a degree in agricultural economics.</p><p>Tim visited the West Bank in the 1970s. On his return he applied to work for the United Nations Association International Service, which promotes the rights enshrined in the UN Charter around the world. Unais wanted to develop a programme in the West Bank and needed a field officer, but had no funds available. The problem was solved when Tim started a research project, a PhD on the agricultural economy of the West Bank, at Aston University, for which he received a grant, while working for Unais. He went on to play a leading role in forming the London Friends of Palestine.</p><p>Tim was a modest, charming man, whose idealism, spirit of adventure and gentle sense of humour left a lasting impression. He is survived by his second wife, Mariana; two sons, Daniel and Benjamin, from a previous marriage; and two grandchildren, Samuel and Zachary.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/nicaragua\">Nicaragua</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/21/tim-coone" (20852 2200) old 27 nil nil ((title nil "Tim Coone obituary") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/21/tim-coone") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/11220?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Atim-coone%3A1897048&ch=From+the+Guardian&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Nicaragua+%28News%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful&c6=Chris+Taylor&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A41&c8=1897048&c9=Article&c10=Obituary&c13=Other+lives+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Tim+Coone+obituary&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FFrom+the+Guardian%2FNicaragua\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>Tim Coone, who has died of cancer aged 60, was a respected foreign correspondent whose life was changed by Nicaragua. He first headed there in 1981 in the optimistic early days of the Sandinista revolution, as a stringer for several media outlets including the BBC World Service, and from his base in the Nicaraguan capital, Managua, covered Central America for most of a turbulent decade, becoming the Financial Times's correspondent.</p><p>Ever resourceful, during the invasion of Panama in 1989, when the US military were preventing the Managua press corps from entering the country, Tim managed to charter a plane, inviting along fellow journalists. As the reporter Joe Gannon remembers: \"Tim being Tim it never occurred to him to take off on his own, get the scoop.\" His peers elected him president of the Managua Foreign Press Club.</p><p>He had brief spells in Argentina in the mid-80s and in Dublin in the 90s, where he clashed with his FT superiors over his take on the Northern Ireland story. In 1994 Tim moved to Mexico as a freelance, later working for the Economist Intelligence Unit.</p><p>He returned to Nicaragua in 1997 and devoted his energies to a project that had long fascinated him: to build a waterway connecting Nicaragua's Pacific coast with the Caribbean Sea. His cost-effective and environmentally sensitive Ecocanal plan attracted influential partners and official approval but to his disappointment the dream remained unfulfilled. Latterly Tim worked to promote renewable energy in Nicaragua.</p><p>He was born in Aberdeen, Maryland, the second son of Kenneth, a US serviceman, and Muriel, a British nurse. The family moved to the UK when Tim was a year old, and his parents subsequently divorced. After King Edward's school, Bath, and Teignmouth grammar school, Devon, he went to Imperial College London, but transferred to Newcastle University, where he completed a degree in agricultural economics.</p><p>Tim visited the West Bank in the 1970s. On his return he applied to work for the United Nations Association International Service, which promotes the rights enshrined in the UN Charter around the world. Unais wanted to develop a programme in the West Bank and needed a field officer, but had no funds available. The problem was solved when Tim started a research project, a PhD on the agricultural economy of the West Bank, at Aston University, for which he received a grant, while working for Unais. He went on to play a leading role in forming the London Friends of Palestine.</p><p>Tim was a modest, charming man, whose idealism, spirit of adventure and gentle sense of humour left a lasting impression. He is survived by his second wife, Mariana; two sons, Daniel and Benjamin, from a previous marriage; and two grandchildren, Samuel and Zachary.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/nicaragua\">Nicaragua</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Nicaragua") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Obituaries") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 15:41:12 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/21/tim-coone") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "From the Guardian") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T15:41:12Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407596175") (media:keywords nil "Nicaragua") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366556616173/tim-coone-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "public domain") (media:description nil "Tim Coone chartered a plane and flew fellow journalists into Panama during the US invasion in 1989")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366556623203/tim-coone-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "public domain") (media:description nil "Tim Coone chartered a plane and flew fellow journalists into Panama during the US invasion in 1989")))) ("FBI accused of 'dropping the ball' on prior questioning of Tamerlan Tsarnaev" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91262?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Afbi-tamerlan-tsarnaev-questioning%3A1897055&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CFBI%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CUS+news%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CUS+Congress%2CUS+politics%2CDzhokhar+Tsarnaev%2CTamerlan+Tsarnaev&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUS+Elections&c6=Matt+Williams&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A31&c8=1897055&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=FBI+accused+of+%27dropping+the+ball%27+on+prior+questioning+of+Tamerlan+Tsarnaev&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Members of Congress ask why no flags were raised after FBI was asked to interview elder Tsarnaev brother in 2011</p><p>The FBI was facing increased scrutiny Sunday over its prior handling of a case involving suspected Boston bomber Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with senior congressional figures demanding answers and accusing the agency of \"dropping the ball\".</p><p>As younger brother Dzhokhar remained in hospital yet to be questioned or charged, Tamerlan – who was killed in a shootout with police early Friday – has been seen by many as the key to understanding how the pair seemingly became radicalised.</p><p>It is now known that the FBI interviewed the elder Tsarnaev brother in 2011 at the request of the Russian government, which raised concern that he had links to Chechen terrorists. On Sunday rebels in the strife-torn country denied any link. But a six-month visit to Russia last year is now being scrutinised to see if Tsarnaev did visit any other countries in the North Caucuses region.</p><p>Michael McCaul, chair of the House Homeland Security Committee, told CNN's State of the Union on Sunday that the FBI had questions to answer.</p><p>\"He was interviewed by the FBI in 2011 and let go. He travelled back to Russia and spent six months there,\" McCaul said.</p><p>On return he immediately posted jihadist videos on YouTube, the Republican lawmaker said. \"Clearly something happened in that six-month timeframe. He radicalised at some point.\"</p><p>McCaul said he wanted to know why no flags were raised on Tsarnaev that would have helped officials track his movements.</p><p>Meanwhile it was reported Sunday that a hold was placed on a citizenship request by the 26-year-old as a result of the FBI's former interest in him.</p><p>An article in the New York Times claimed officials at the Department of Homeland Security decided not to grant his application after a routine background check uncovered the 2011 interview by agents.</p><p>The FBI has not said publicly who requested that they look into the activities of the elder brother, but it has been widely reported that it was the Russian government.</p><p>In a statement late Friday, the agency admitted interviewing Tamerlan and other family members.</p><p>\"The FBI did not find any terrorism activity, domestic of foreign, and those results were provided to the foreign government in the summer of 2011,\" it said.</p><p>But on Sunday, the agency was accused of having \"dropped the ball\" regarding the older Tsarnaev brother.</p><p>\"The FBI missed a lot of things,\" senator Lindsey Graham told CNN's State of the Union.</p><p>Meanwhile fellow Republican Peter King, chairman of the House subcommittee on counterterrorism, blasted the FBI for alleged failings in the case.</p><p>\"This is the firth case I'm aware of where the FBI has failed to stop someone,\" he told Fox News Sunday, going on to cite the cases of al-Qaida recruiter Anwar al-Awlaki, Little Rock shooter Carlos Bledsoe, the accused Fort Hood killer Nidal Malik and alleged American-Pakistani terrorist David Coleman Headley.</p><p>\"This is the latest in a series of cases like this … where the FBI is given information about someone as being a potential terrorist. They look at them, and then hey don't take action and then they go out and commit murders,\" King said.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/fbi\">FBI</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.gua