genre%29%2CBooks%2CChristianity+%28News%29%2CCulture%2CCatholicism+%28News%29%2CJudaism+%28News%29%2CReligion+%28News%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful&c6=Richard+Coles&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+09%3A00&c8=1894307&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Silence%3A+A+Christian+History+by+Diarmaid+MacCulloch+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FBooks%2FReligion\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Diarmaid MacCulloch considers the role of silence in church tradition and finds it not always a positive one</p><p>That silence should be essential to Christian traditions is actually rather a surprise, considering the noisy world from which it springs. In Judaism, disputatious, full of sound and fury, there is nevertheless a minority witness in the prophecy of Isaiah, which speaks of the arrival of a suffering servant, silent in the face of injustice. For Christians, this figure points irresistibly to Jesus Christ, dumbly facing down his accusers, and all but confirms him as the Messiah, the chosen one of God. Early Christianity can be interpreted as the meeting of noisy Jewish monotheism and mute Greek thought, and the silence in Christian tradition seems of a very Platonic sort, wordless before the ineffable, inscrutable, inexpressible mystery of the divine. This has tended to be more at home at the Catholic end of the Christian spectrum in our own time and contributes, MacCulloch suggests, to another profoundly regrettable form of silence: the church's self-imposed omerta when scandal threatens to break. Perhaps, in light of that, we might impose on ourselves another kind of silence, and listen, in humility and with penitence, to God speaking in God's endlessly surprising and confounding ways.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/religion\">Religion</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/christianity\">Christianity</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/catholicism\">Catholicism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/judaism\">Judaism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/religion\">Religion</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/richard-coles\">Richard Coles</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/21/silence-christian-history-macculloch-review" (20851 40079) obsolete 30 nil nil ((title nil "Silence: A Christian History by Diarmaid MacCulloch – review") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/21/silence-christian-history-macculloch-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/78861?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Asilence-christian-history-macculloch-review%3A1894307&ch=Books&c3=Obs&c4=Religion+%28Books+genre%29%2CBooks%2CChristianity+%28News%29%2CCulture%2CCatholicism+%28News%29%2CJudaism+%28News%29%2CReligion+%28News%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful&c6=Richard+Coles&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+09%3A00&c8=1894307&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Silence%3A+A+Christian+History+by+Diarmaid+MacCulloch+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FBooks%2FReligion\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Diarmaid MacCulloch considers the role of silence in church tradition and finds it not always a positive one</p><p>That silence should be essential to Christian traditions is actually rather a surprise, considering the noisy world from which it springs. In Judaism, disputatious, full of sound and fury, there is nevertheless a minority witness in the prophecy of Isaiah, which speaks of the arrival of a suffering servant, silent in the face of injustice. For Christians, this figure points irresistibly to Jesus Christ, dumbly facing down his accusers, and all but confirms him as the Messiah, the chosen one of God. Early Christianity can be interpreted as the meeting of noisy Jewish monotheism and mute Greek thought, and the silence in Christian tradition seems of a very Platonic sort, wordless before the ineffable, inscrutable, inexpressible mystery of the divine. This has tended to be more at home at the Catholic end of the Christian spectrum in our own time and contributes, MacCulloch suggests, to another profoundly regrettable form of silence: the church's self-imposed omerta when scandal threatens to break. Perhaps, in light of that, we might impose on ourselves another kind of silence, and listen, in humility and with penitence, to God speaking in God's endlessly surprising and confounding ways.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/religion\">Religion</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/christianity\">Christianity</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/catholicism\">Catholicism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/judaism\">Judaism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/religion\">Religion</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/richard-coles\">Richard Coles</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Religion") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Books") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Christianity") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Catholicism") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Judaism") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Religion") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Observer") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 08:00:15 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/21/silence-christian-history-macculloch-review") (dc:creator nil "Richard Coles") (dc:subject nil "Books") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T08:00:15Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407236225"))) ("Beppe Grillo attacks Italian president's re-election" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/17443?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abeppe-grillo-italian-president-napolitano%3A1897079&ch=World+news&c3=Guardian&c4=Beppe+Grillo%2CItalian+elections+2013%2CFive+Star+Movement%2CItaly+%28News%29%2CSilvio+Berlusconi%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUnclassifed+Contributors&c6=Reuters&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+06%3A21&c8=1897079&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Beppe+Grillo+attacks+Italian+president%27s+re-election&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBeppe+Grillo\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Napolitano re-election is desperate attempt to retain power by discredited establishment, says leader of Five Star Movement</p><p>The leader of Italy's anti-establishment Five Star Movement, Beppe Grillo, hascriticised the re-election of President Giorgio Napolitano as a desperate attempt to retain power by a discredited establishment.</p><p>The eurozone's third largest economy is still without a government two months after a general election, has scarcely grown in 20 years and is grappling with the highest level of unemployment in decades.</p><p>Talks on the formation of a new administration are expected to resume in the coming week, with the parties under pressure from Napolitano to reach a deal.</p><p>The broad right-left agreement to hand Napolitano another seven-year mandate could end Italy's political impasse, which resulted after no single force emerged from February's election with a workable majority in parliament.</p><p>Grillo's movement backed Stefano Rodota, a leftist academic, while Napolitano was elected by Silvio Berlusconi's centre-right bloc, the outgoing prime minister Mario Monti's centrist movement, and the badly divided centre-left Democratic Party (PD).</p><p>Grillo, whose vow to kick out the old guard won his Five Star Movement one in four votes in its first national election, called the presidential vote \"a cunning little institutional coup\" designed to keep the old parties in power.</p><p>\"They have stolen a year of time. I don't think we can accept this,\" he told a press conference, his first since the February election.</p><p>The 87-year-old Napolitano's re-election – the first time a president has been asked to serve a second term – gives him the option of calling a snap parliamentary election, allowing him more leverage to pressure the parties to reach a deal.</p><p>Napolitano now has the power to dissolve parliament, which he did not have in the final months of his first term.</p><p>He is likely to spell out his strategy in an address to parliament on Monday, but he has already made it clear that he favours forming a government to avoid a potentially destabilising new election.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/beppe-grillo\">Beppe Grillo</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/italian-elections-2013\">Italian elections 2013</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/five-star-movement\">Five Star Movement</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/italy\">Italy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/silvio-berlusconi\">Silvio Berlusconi</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/beppe-grillo-italian-president-napolitano" (20852 8247) old 20 nil nil ((title nil "Beppe Grillo attacks Italian president's re-election") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/beppe-grillo-italian-president-napolitano") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/17443?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abeppe-grillo-italian-president-napolitano%3A1897079&ch=World+news&c3=Guardian&c4=Beppe+Grillo%2CItalian+elections+2013%2CFive+Star+Movement%2CItaly+%28News%29%2CSilvio+Berlusconi%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUnclassifed+Contributors&c6=Reuters&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+06%3A21&c8=1897079&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Beppe+Grillo+attacks+Italian+president%27s+re-election&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBeppe+Grillo\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Napolitano re-election is desperate attempt to retain power by discredited establishment, says leader of Five Star Movement</p><p>The leader of Italy's anti-establishment Five Star Movement, Beppe Grillo, hascriticised the re-election of President Giorgio Napolitano as a desperate attempt to retain power by a discredited establishment.</p><p>The eurozone's third largest economy is still without a government two months after a general election, has scarcely grown in 20 years and is grappling with the highest level of unemployment in decades.</p><p>Talks on the formation of a new administration are expected to resume in the coming week, with the parties under pressure from Napolitano to reach a deal.</p><p>The broad right-left agreement to hand Napolitano another seven-year mandate could end Italy's political impasse, which resulted after no single force emerged from February's election with a workable majority in parliament.</p><p>Grillo's movement backed Stefano Rodota, a leftist academic, while Napolitano was elected by Silvio Berlusconi's centre-right bloc, the outgoing prime minister Mario Monti's centrist movement, and the badly divided centre-left Democratic Party (PD).</p><p>Grillo, whose vow to kick out the old guard won his Five Star Movement one in four votes in its first national election, called the presidential vote \"a cunning little institutional coup\" designed to keep the old parties in power.</p><p>\"They have stolen a year of time. I don't think we can accept this,\" he told a press conference, his first since the February election.</p><p>The 87-year-old Napolitano's re-election – the first time a president has been asked to serve a second term – gives him the option of calling a snap parliamentary election, allowing him more leverage to pressure the parties to reach a deal.</p><p>Napolitano now has the power to dissolve parliament, which he did not have in the final months of his first term.</p><p>He is likely to spell out his strategy in an address to parliament on Monday, but he has already made it clear that he favours forming a government to avoid a potentially destabilising new election.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/beppe-grillo\">Beppe Grillo</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/italian-elections-2013\">Italian elections 2013</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/five-star-movement\">Five Star Movement</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/italy\">Italy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/silvio-berlusconi\">Silvio Berlusconi</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Beppe Grillo") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Italian elections 2013") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Five Star Movement") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Italy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Silvio Berlusconi") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 17:21:59 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/beppe-grillo-italian-president-napolitano") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T17:34:18Z") (dc:type nil "Ar